  {
    "text": "Start Here\nAt least one player should familiarize themselves \nwith the base rules in this book (no need for every-\none to read through unless they really want to). The \nadventure included in the GM’s Guide is designed \nto introduce the rules as you play.",
    "page": 5,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "If you’re new to TTRPGs, use one of the pre-\nmade heroes (included in your digital downloads \nor at nimbleRPG.com/start). Level 1 for all of the \nclasses is designed to be easy to pick up, giving a \nsmall flavor of the class and introducing the rules \ngradually without being overwhelming. Complexity \nand tactical depth is layered on as you level up and \nprogress through an adventure.",
    "page": 5,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "If you’re experienced with RPGs, feel free \nto create your own hero from scratch (see “Char-\nacter Creation” on pg. 18). When building your",
    "page": 5,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "hero, perhaps what will have the largest impact on \nhow you interact with the world is your hero’s class. \nStart there. Then you can flesh out other important \naspects of your character’s ancestry, background, \nand what languages you know, as well as your stats \nand any equipment you have. You can do these \nsteps in any order, filling out your character sheet \nas you go. Now, go start playing!",
    "page": 5,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Videos, Digital Downloads, FAQ, and More\nVisit nimbleRPG.com/start \nfor everything you need to \njump into the game: pre-\nmade characters, step-by-step \ninstructional videos, answers \nto FAQs, and other handy \ndownloadable resources!",
    "page": 5,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "How to Be a Good Player\nPay attention. Ask questions. Take notes. \nThe more questions you ask, the more information \nyou’ll have to work with, and you’ll be able to make \nmore interesting decisions.",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Be creative! Frequently, the answer to a prob-\nlem isn’t found on your character sheet. A hammer \n(or anything else) can be used in lots of ways!",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Embrace failure. You shouldn’t try to fail, but \nsome of the best moments in a game can come from \na failed roll or bad decision. Go with it!",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Respect everyone else’s time. Swift, subop-\ntimal decisions are better than slow, optimal ones. \nThey will tend to be more fun anyway! If you can’t \ndecide what to do on your turn, attack and pass. \nThink when everyone else isn’t waiting on you. Also, \narrive on time.",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Share the spotlight. If you’ve been rolling or \ntalking more than everyone else, call on your par-\ntymates to help you; shine the spotlight on them.",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Sneaky characters shouldn’t spend a bunch of \ntime sneaking around a dungeon without the rest \nof the party. A charismatic hero might be taking \nthe lead in a negotiation (that’s fine!), but he may \nwant to call on his Berserker pal for a bit of extra \nleverage. “Ragnar, would you like to have a word \nwith this stubborn gentleman while the rest of us \nstep outside?”",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Treat the world realistically. If you insult \n(or kill) other characters you come across, expect \nconsequences! If you negotiate and haggle with",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "every merchant, your reputation as penny pinch-\ners will likely become widespread. If you do some-\nthing foolish in front of a king, expect to be jailed \n(or worse). If you heal an ally, deal lots of damage, \nor always use the same tactics, expect the bad guys \nto catch on and adapt.",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Describe your actions, not mechanics. The \nGame Master (GM, the player running the game) \nwill tell you if you need to roll any dice. If your idea \nis good enough, you may not need to!",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "No: “Can I make an Examination check?”\nYes: “I want to search the books and paintings \non the walls, looking for a secret door.”",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "No: “I make an attack roll.”\nYes: “I smack that goblin with my sword!”",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "No: “Save your reaction, I’m only at 2 Wounds, I \ncan take three more.”\nYes: “Leave me be, I can take the hit!”",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Note. If these examples don’t mean \nanything to you, that’s okay, you’ll get \nthe hang of it after playing once or twice.",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Be gracious to the GM. They put a lot of effort \ninto creating the game; avoid arguing over rulings. \nGive them a break sometimes and offer to run a ses-\nsion for them! Bring snacks.",
    "page": 6,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Arcana (INT). Your understanding of magi-\ncal phenomena, spells, and enchantments. With \nArcana, you can identify magical effects, decipher \narcane symbols, and discern the properties of mag-\nical items. It also grants insights into the abilities \nand weaknesses of magical beings like Aberrations, \nElementals, and Oozes.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Examination (INT). Your aptitude for thor-\nough analysis and deduction. Use Examination \nto diagnose injuries, determine causes of death, \nuncover clues, and unravel the workings of traps or \nmechanical devices. It also grants insights into the \nabilities and weaknesses of Constructs.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Finesse (DEX). Your ability to use your hands \nand feet in careful ways. Use Finesse for activities \nsuch as picking locks, disarming traps, piloting \nvehicles, tinkering, card tricks, stealing or plant-\ning items, climbing a mossy wall, or any other task \nthat requires precise, careful movement.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Influence (WIL). Your persuasiveness, charm, \nand ability to influence others through charisma \nor cunning. Use Influence to convince or deceive \npeople, negotiate deals, build trust, win allies to",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "your cause, or put on a captivating performance.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Insight (WIL). Your ability to understand \npeople and situations beyond the obvious. Use \nInsight to sense motives, detect lies, read hidden \nemotions, make sense of clues, and when faced \nwith uncertainty—you can think ahead or just “get” \nwhat is happening. Insight can be used to retroac-\ntively change situations:",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Player: “Oh no! I forgot to buy rope back in town!” \nGM: “Give me an Insight check; maybe your hero \nwould have thought about it.”",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Might (STR). Your ability to apply strength \neffectively. Use Might for lifting heavy objects, \nbreaking through obstacles, climbing, swimming, \njumping, or performing feats of strength.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Lore (INT). Your understanding of the history \nof civilization, kingdoms, and religions. Use Lore to \nrecall historical events and grasp the significance \nof cultural practices. It extends to knowledge of the \nabilities and behavior of Celestials, Dragons, Fey, \nFiends, Giants, Humanoids, and Undead.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Stats\nHeroes have 4 stats that impact their effectiveness in various tasks: 2 Key Stats crucial to their class and 2 \nSecondary Stats. The maximum a hero’s stat can typically go is +5 .",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "KEY. When an ability or spell references “KEY,” use one of your Key Stats. If a stat is listed before a die roll, roll a number \nof dice equal to the stat. For example, “WIL d8” means that if your WIL is 2, you roll 2d8 (two eight-sided dice).",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Strength (STR). Your raw physical power and \nresilience, endurance, and resistance to harm. \nAffects STR weapon damage, resistance to Wounds, \nHP recovery, Concentration, STR saves, carrying \ncapacity, Grappling, and the Might skill.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Dexterity (DEX). Your agility, reflexes, and \nprecision with blades or bows. Affects DEX weapon \ndamage, Initiative, DEX saves, Grappling, and can \ncontribute to Armor, as well as the Stealth and \nFinesse skills.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Intelligence (INT). Your Intelligence reflects \nknowledge and reasoning across fields like the \narcane, tactics, or street smarts. Affects languages, \nspellcasting, use of wands, spell scrolls, INT saves, \nas well as the Arcana, Examination, and Lore skills.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Will (WIL). Your force of personality, courage, \nand wisdom. Will shapes your interactions with \nboth nature and society. Affects spellcasting and WIL \nsaves, as well as the Insight, Influence, Naturecraft, \nand Perception skills.\nSkills\nSkills gauge how well your hero interacts with the world. Whenever you tell the GM what you are doing, \nthey may ask you to use one of your skills.",
    "page": 8,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Naturecraft (WIL). Your expertise in wilder-\nness survival, navigation, tracking, and the han-\ndling of animals. Use Naturecraft to thrive in the \nwild, identify flora, fauna, and track creatures with \nprecision. It encompasses knowledge of Beasts, \nMonstrosities, and Plants, providing insights into \ntheir behavior, habitats, and characteristics.",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Perception (WIL). Your overall ability to notice \nsubtle details in your surroundings. Use Percep-",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "tion to spot hidden objects, detect secret passages, \nsense subtle environmental changes, and sense \nwhen you’re being followed or observed. It encom-\npasses your ability to pick up on non-obvious cues, \nand hidden threats.",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Stealth (DEX). Your proficiency in staying \nunseen and moving quietly. Use Stealth to hide, \nslip past guards, evade detection, and move with-\nout drawing attention.\nSkill Checks & Saves\nWhen you want to affect the world (convince an NPC, spot a trap, pick a lock, etc.), the GM may call for a \nskill check. Roll 1d20 and add your skill (the max bonus a skill can ever have is +12). If the total meets or \nexceeds the Difficulty Challenge (DC), you succeed; otherwise, you fail. A roll of 1 always fails regardless \nof any other bonuses, while a roll of 20 always succeeds. The DC varies based on the task:",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Size\nSome spells and abilities affect differently sized objects or creatures. For size, use the following guidelines:",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• Tiny can be carried in a typical pocket (many can comfortably fit in 1 space). \n\t• Small can be carried in a backpack (2 can comfortably fit in 1 space).\n\t• Medium is the average human size (1 can comfortably fit in 1 space).\n\t• Large is roughly the size of a bear (1 can comfortably fit in a 2x2 area).\n\t• Huge is roughly the size of a small house (1 can comfortably fit in a 3x3 area).\n\t• Gargantuan can be as large as a castle keep (1 can fill a 4x4 area or greater).",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• Easy: Spotting a large Ogre crouched behind a",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "small bush might be a DC 8 Perception check.\n\t• Medium: A hidden doorway behind a bookcase",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "might be a DC 12 Examination check. \n\t• Challenging: Calming an injured Owlbear stuck",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "in a trap may be a DC 15 Naturecraft check.\n\t• Very Difficult: Intuiting the true intentions of a",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "trained Spy may be a DC 18 Insight check. \n\t• Extremely Difficult: Disarming an ancient",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "legendary trap may be a DC 20+ Finesse check.",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Saves. When the world affects you, roll a save \ninstead of a skill check. Roll 1d20 and add the rel-\nevant stat. A roll of 1 always fails, 20 always saves. \nYou can choose to fail any save instead of rolling.",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• STR Save. When your overall fitness and physi-",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "cality is tested. STR helps resist forced movement, \nrestraint, poison, and extreme temperatures.",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• DEX Save. When your agility or speed is tested.",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "DEX helps you dive for cover in an explosion or \nstay on your feet while running across icy terrain.\n\t• INT Save. When your intelligence is tested. INT",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "helps you see though tricks and illusions.\n\t• WIL Save. When your courage or personality is",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "tested. WIL helps you resist charm or fear effects.",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• Unless otherwise noted, the DC for effects a hero",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "causes is 10+KEY. \n\t• When making saves, each hero has 1 advan-",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "taged save (+), 1 disadvantaged save (–), and \n2 neutral saves.",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Example. A Berserker (STR+, INT–) would roll all of \nhis STR saves with advantage and all of his INT saves \nwith disadvantage (see next page).",
    "page": 9,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Advantage & Disadvantage\nIf you are ever in a favorable situation, the GM may allow you to roll with advantage. To do this, roll 1 addi-\ntional die of the same type and remove the lowest (see examples below). Alternatively, if the situation is \ngrim or your idea is a long shot, you may have to roll with disadvantage (removing the highest die instead).",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "If you have multiple instances of advantage or disadvantage, for each one, roll an extra die and remove \nthe lowest (for advantage) or the highest (for disadvantage). Each instance of advantage cancels out one \ninstance of disadvantage before you roll.",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Hit Points (HP) represent your ability to endure \ndamage. Damage reduces your HP (which can’t go \nbelow 0). When reduced to 0 HP, gain 1 Wound; \nyou also gain the Dying condition until you regain \nHP. While Dying, actions are limited to 1, Concen-\ntration is broken, and you are at risk of further seri-\nous harm:",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• \tAttacking/casting spells causes 1 Wound unless",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "you make a DC 10 STR save.\n\t• Taking damage while Dying causes 2 Wounds;",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wounds are serious injuries you’ve taken; they are \na long term gauge of how close you are to death. \nHP can usually be recovered quickly, but Wounds \nmay take many days of resting to fully recover from \n(usually 1/Safe Rest).",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Death\nYou die when you have taken 6 Wounds (unless you \nhave an ability that changes this number). There are \nways to revive a hero who has died, but they are rare \nand often come at a very steep cost.",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Some abilities or effects may grant temporary HP \n(temp HP); these are reduced first when taking \ndamage. Temp HP do not combine: If a hero has \ntemp HP and would gain more, they instead choose \nwhich amount to keep. They expire after a Safe Rest.",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Hit Dice\nHit Dice (HD) represent your ability to quickly recu-\nperate from minor injuries and are spent to regain \nHP. Heroes start with a max of 1 Hit Die at level 1, \nand this limit increases by 1 each time they level \nup. Hit Dice are recovered during a Safe Rest (see \n“RESTING & DOWNTIME” on page 16).",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Gritty Dying Rules. Optional rules \nfor a more challenging or “old school” \nstyle of game: You can reduce the max \nnumber of Wounds heroes have. Any-\nwhere from a max of 5 Wounds for slightly harder, all \nthe way down to 1–2 Wounds for a very lethal game!  \n \nYou can also have each Wound impose a cumulative \n–1 penalty to rolls: skill checks, saves, or even ALL rolls!",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "(If you’re a real glutton for punishment.)",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Example 1. Greataxe (2d6) with advantage.",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Roll 1 additional die and remove the lowest.",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "You hit! See attack rules on pg. 13 for more.",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Example 2. Greataxe (2d6) with disadvantage 2. Roll \n2 additional dice, remove the 2 highest. If there is a tie,",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "always remove dice from left to right. You miss!",
    "page": 10,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Speed & Range\nA character’s Speed is how fast they can move, \nwhich, unless otherwise noted, is 6. Often play is \ndone on a grid with 1 inch squares or hexagons \nrepresenting roughly 5 ft. or 1 meter each. So a \nhero with a speed of 6 can travel up to 6 spaces \nhorizontally or diagonally.",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "You can move through spaces occupied by allies \n(or enemies as difficult terrain: half speed), as long \nas you don’t end movement in an occupied space.",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Alternate Options. For a quicker, \nmore loose game, you can forego \ncounting spaces and measure typi-\ncal movement roughly from pinkie \nto thumb. Slightly less for players \nwith large hands (or slower characters), a bit more for \nour tiny-handed friends (or faster characters).",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Range & Reach\nCertain abilities, weapons, and spells have a spec-\nified Range or Reach, which determines how far \naway your target can be affected. If none is specified, \ndefault to Reach 1.",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• In Melee. If any enemy is adjacent to you, your",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Ranged attacks are made with disadvantage \n(Reach attacks are not so affected).\n\t• Long Range. You can gain disadvantage 1 to",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "gain +2 Range on any Ranged attack (max +6).",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Falling & Forced Movement\nWhen a character is forcibly moved but stopped by \nan obstacle, they take 1d6 bludgeoning damage \nfor every space this movement is shortened. If \nthey hit another creature, both creatures split this \ndamage. Falling inflicts 1d6 bludgeoning damage \nfor every 10 ft. fallen (2 spaces).",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Abstracted Distances. If preferred, you can use a \nmore abstracted system of distance just as well. Use \nClose, Midrange, and Far. A move from Midrange \ncan traverse to Close or Far. Close creatures can be \naffected Reach/Range 4; Midrange, up to 6; beyond \nthat is Far. As always, the GM will adjudicate unclear \nsituations and which creatures are affected by abilities \nwith an area of effect.",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Concentration\nSome activities require Concentration to maintain. \nA character can only concentrate on one activity at \na time. Whenever a character is crit while concen-\ntrating, they must make a DC 10 STR save. Failing \nthis means Concentration is broken and the activity \nfails. Concentration is automatically broken when-\never a character drops to 0 HP or is incapacitated.\nCover & Hiding\nA creature mostly obscured from line of sight \n(standing behind a tree, a larger ally, a knocked \nover table, in poor lighting, etc.) has Cover and \nimposes disadvantage on attacks against them. A \ncreature completely obscured from view has Full \nCover and cannot typically be targeted by an attack.",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "To hide in combat, you must have Cover from the \ncreatures you are attempting to hide from and use \nan action to make a DC 15 Stealth check (if you \nhave Full Cover, you succeed automatically). The \nfirst attack you make while hidden is made with \nadvantage, then you are no longer hidden. If this \nattack kills the enemy and no other enemy can see \nyou, you may remain hidden instead.",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Monsters Are Smart! They may catch on to heroes \nusing the same tactics over and over again!\nGrappling\nYou can attempt to grab another creature provided \nyou are within Reach and have at least 1 arm free \n(or some other way to grab them). On a failed STR \nor DEX save (DC 10+STR or DEX), a target:",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• your size or smaller, is Grappled.\n\t• larger than you, you gain the Riding condition.\nForced movement (pushing a grappler away), inca-\npacitation, or spending an action and succeeding \non a STR or DEX save can end it.",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Restrained. Functions like Grappled, but is caused \nby objects (e.g., chains, rope, roots) and ignores size \nrestrictions. It can also be ended through any logical \nmeans, such as picking a lock or cutting/burning rope.",
    "page": 11,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Conditions\nSome attacks, traps, spells, or other effects can also inflict conditions—usually negative effects other than \ndamage. Some conditions are temporary, lasting as little as a single round; others may last until cured in \nsome way, and some can be ended by using an action to make an appropriate save.",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• Blinded. Can’t see. Attacks against you have",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "advantage, and your attacks have disadvantage.\n\t• Bloodied. At half HP or less.\n\t• Charmed. Sees the charmer as an ally. Charmer has",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "advantage on social interactions with you.\n\t• Dazed. Heroes: lose 1 action; monsters: can",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "perform one less action on their next turn.\n\t• Dying. At 0 HP. Taking damage while dying",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "causes 2 Wounds, a crit causes 3 instead.\n\t• Frightened. Disadvantage on rolls when source  of",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "fear is nearby; speed halved when moving closer to it.\n\t• Grappled/Restrained. Cannot move. Attacks",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "against you have advantage. \n\t• Hampered. Any creature with their actions or",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "movement reduced (e.g., Dazed, Grappled, Prone, \nDifficult Terrain).\n\t• Incapacitated. Can’t do anything. Attacks against",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "you have advantage, and melee attacks that hit, crit.\n\t• Invisible. Cannot be seen. Your attacks have advan-",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "tage, and attacks against you have disadvantage.\n\t• Petrified. Incapacitated. You have all the benefits and",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "drawbacks of being a rock! Immune to most damage",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "except from large explosions, picks, or similar tools.\n\t• Poisoned. Disadvantage on rolls.\n\t• Prone. Movement costs twice as much, and",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "disadvantage on attacks. Melee attacks against \nyou have advantage; Ranged have disadvantage. \nSpend 3 spaces of your Speed to stand up.\n\t• Riding. You move with the creature you are",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "riding. Any attacks that miss you, strike them.\n\t• Slowed. Speed halved during your next turn.\n\t• Taunted. Disadvantage on attacks except against",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "the most recent taunter.\n\t• Wounded. Has any Wounds (typically 6 Wounds",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Other Minor Statuses. Minor statuses (Smoldering, \nCharged, Distracted, etc.) do nothing on their own and \nend whenever combat does. Some spells and \nabilities have additional effects against \nsuch targets.",
    "page": 12,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Heroic Actions\nOn your turn, heroes get 3 actions to attack, move around the battlefield, cast spells, etc. Generally doing \nany single thing in combat costs 1 action. Some very strong spells or special abilities may take more time \nand thus cost more actions.",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "All 3 actions recharge at the end of your turn, so there’s no need to save them up. Spend them all on \nyour turn and when you’re done, you get them all back!",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Any spell or ability that can harm an \nenemy counts as an attack. Roll the \ndie listed on the spell, weapon, or ability, and \ndeal that much damage. However, if you roll a 1, \nyou miss, and the attack has no effect. For attacks \nwith multiple dice, the leftmost die is called the \nPrimary Die. It determines whether the attack \nis a hit or a miss.",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Exploding Critical Hits. Rolling the max on \na Primary Die is a critical hit (crit). When you crit, \nroll the Primary Die again, and add the result to \nthe total. Repeat this each time you roll the maxi-\nmum—there’s no limit, except your luck! Crits also \nignore monster armor (see pg. 14).",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Rushed Attacks. A hero may attack more than \nonce on their turn, but these additional attacks are \nrushed, imposing cumulative disadvantage for \neach additional attack after the first—increasing the \nchance to miss and lowering the average damage \nfor subsequent attacks. For abilities that trigger a \nsave (e.g. Grappling),  enemies roll with increasing \ninstances of advantage instead.",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Cast Spell\nCasting a spell requires a hero to have 1 \nhand free (or a held spellcasting focus), \nthe ability to speak, and may require mana as well. \nA spell’s mana cost is equal to its spell tier; cantrips \ncost no mana (see “Spells” on page 44 for more).",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Upcasting Spells. Some spells have a greater \neffect for each additional mana spent on them. A \nhero can upcast a spell only up to the tier they \nhave unlocked.",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Move\nA character can move up to their speed \n(6 spaces, unless otherwise noted). \nThis movement can be broken up with other \nactions if desired, and a hero can use multiple \nactions to Move multiple times in one turn. When \nin Difficult Terrain, movement speed is halved. \nMoving on a climbable surface (trees, a cliffside, \ncertain buildings, etc.) counts as Difficult Terrain.",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "A great way to include creativity and \nrole-playing in combat. Choose one of \nthe following and then make a DC 12 skill check to:",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• Ask a Question. About a weakness, ability, or",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "immediate plans of enemies, the environment, \nstory, etc. The GM will answer honestly.\n\t• Create an Opening. Increase the next Pri-",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "mary Die Roll against a target by 1 this round.\n\t• Anticipate Danger. Reduce all Primary Dice",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Which Skill To Use? Whatever skill you use must \nmake sense based on the circumstances. For example, \nif you’re close to an enemy, you could use Might to \ncreate an opening, but against an enemy that is far \naway, that may not make sense. Or if you want to ask \na question about the weaknesses of an elemental, \nyou’d likely use Arcana.",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Monsters Are Smart! You cannot assess using \nthe same skill more than once in a single encoun-\nter, as your foes adapt to your tactics. You’ll need \nto stay creative!",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Free Actions. These do not cost an action or any other resource (e.g., mana) unless otherwise specified. Heroes can",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "do simple tasks (open an unlocked door, shout a simple phrase, drop an item, end concentration, etc.) for free 1/ turn.",
    "page": 14,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Defend\nReduce damage from any single attack \nby your Armor whenever you use this \nreaction. At the GM’s discretion, \nsome damage may not be avoidable (e.g., psychic \ndamage, or some areas of effect).",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Interpose\nIf a creature within 2 spaces would be \nstruck with an attack, you can push \nthem out of the way and become the \nnew target of the attack. You enter their space and \nmove them to an adjacent space of your choice.",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Interpose AND Defend? Yes! As long as you have \nenough actions to spend, you can Interpose and \nDefend at the same time. However, you won’t be able \nto do either reaction again until your next turn is over \nsince each of those is limited to 1/round.",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Opportunity Attack\nA melee attack made with disadvantage \nagainst an adjacent enemy as it willingly \nmoves away. Monsters do not make \nopportunity attacks, only heroes can.",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Help\nGrant an ally advantage on a roll if you \ncan reasonably explain to the GM how \nyou could help in a given situation (limit: \none Help reaction for each roll). The GM may call for \na skill check or grant advantage automatically, \ndepending on how good the idea is.",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Teamwork! Help as a Heroic \nReaction is a fantastic way to bring \nteamwork, role-playing, and cre-\nativity into a combat encounter. Did \nyour buddy fail? Maybe not! Think quickly \nand see if you can help them succeed.",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Heroic Reactions\nReactions cost 1 action and are performed when it is not your turn. A hero can perform each reaction no \nmore than 1/round, and they will start their turn with fewer actions. The reactions are:",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Monsters & Armor\nMost monsters are unarmored, but some tougher foes might have Medium \nArmor: they take damage from only the dice rolled, ignoring all damage \nmodifiers (unless they are negative). Monsters with Heavy Armor take \nonly half the damage from the dice, likewise ignoring damage modifiers.",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Crits and damage vulnerabilities ignore monster armor. \nThis means that different heroes and different weapons, spells, and abilities will \nbe more or less effective against various kinds of armor.",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Minions\nMinions are weak enemies that will die from any amount of damage. They move and \nattack at the same time, cannot crit, and their feeble attacks can be Defended against \nas if they were a single attack. Dealing a large amount of damage to a minion can (at \nthe GM’s discretion) overflow to other minions within range as well.",
    "page": 15,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "A combat encounter begins when the GM tells the \nparty to “Roll Initiative!” Each hero rolls 1d20 and \nadds their Initiative bonus (typically their DEX). A \nsingle digit means they start combat with 1 action. \n2 digits, they start combat with 2. A result of 20+ (or \na natural 20) means they get all 3 actions! Regard-\nless of what a hero rolls on Initiative, at the end of \ntheir turn they gain all 3 actions back.",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Surprise. Occasionally a party may maneu-\nver themselves so adeptly that their enemy is \ncompletely caught off guard. In this case, the GM \nmay grant the party advantage on Initiative, or in \nextreme cases, they may not need to roll Initiative \nat all—the GM can allow each Hero to start with all",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "A Note on Surprise. Merely being hidden or",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "in extreme cases, \nthe heroes may \nautomatically \nstart combat with \nonly 1 action, or \nthe monsters may all go first.",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "When combat begins, by default, \nthe heroes go first. Whichever \nplayer is ready first goes first (or \nwhoever makes the most sense \nstory-wise), with play proceeding \naround the table clockwise.",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "though some monsters may be fast enough to act \nsooner in the round. A monster (or monster group) \nshould act at the same time each round.",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Encourage teamwork, be flexible. If players \nwant to strategically switch their turns for one round \nto facilitate teamwork or execute a tactical plan, the \nGM can allow this at his/her discretion. This should be \ndone only occasionally, though, to avoid slowing the \ngame down or losing track of who has taken their turn.",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Playing virtually? You can go in webcam order, \nalphabetically, or however is easiest to track!",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "A Turn is when 1 individual hero or monster \ngroup acts. A typical turn takes roughly 6 seconds \nof “in-world“ time. A Round is when all players and \nmonsters have taken a turn acting. An Encounter \nis all of the rounds in a particular combat.",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "1/Turn Abilities. If you perform one on your turn, \nand can find a way to perform it on another creature’s \nturn, you can do it again (e.g., Sneak Attack combined \nwith Opportunity Attack or Coordinated Strike!).  \n \n1/Round Abilities. These reset whenever your own",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "turn begins (e.g., when you Defend, you cannot do so \nagain until your turn comes back around).",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "For activities that cost more than 1 action, your \nactions can be spent over multiple turns in combat \nas long as Concentration is maintained and you do \nnot perform other actions or reactions in the mean-\ntime (unless they are free).",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Example. Book, the Mage, wants to cast Glacier Strike \n(3 actions), but only has 1 action left. He’ll spend 1 \naction on this turn to start casting the spell, and on his \nnext turn spend 2 more to finish casting it. He’s taking \na risk, though: he can’t Defend himself and may need \nto rely on his party to protect him.",
    "page": 16,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Field Rests\nWhile out adventuring, heroes can take Field Rests \nto regain HP.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Catch Breath. Requires at least 10 minutes to \ntend to your injuries. Expend any number of Hit Dice \none at a time (roll them and add your STR to each), \nand regain that many HP.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Make Camp. If you rest for at least 8 hours with \nfood and sleep, take the maximum value for each \nHit Die you expend instead of rolling. Add your STR \nto each Hit Die as usual.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "What if I Have Negative STR? Your frail body doesn’t \nrecover as quickly as others. Subtract your STR from \neach HD you expend.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Safe Rests\nSafe Rests take place in a safe location designated \nby your GM, typically lodging at an inn overnight—\nbut could also be at a secret oasis, a well-stocked \ncabin in the woods, near a sacred shrine, or the like. \nCamping in the open wilderness or in a dungeon is \nnot sufficient for gaining the benefits of a Safe Rest.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "After a Safe Rest, heroes recover all of their HP, \nHit Dice, mana (and other class-specific resources), \nand heal 1 Wound. Safe Rests are a great opportu-\nnity for downtime activities as well.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Rest for HOW Long?! If your table prefers to largely \nskip downtime activities and narrate past a week of \nresting, that’s okay too! For a more realistic convales-\ncence time, 1 week per wound recovered may make \nmore sense.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Lodging\nThe cheapest rooms at an inn save you money but \nmay lead to complications. On the other hand, \nsome inns may allow you to pay a premium for a \nnicer room and amenities, giving you a Temporary \nBoon. Typical prices (each person/day): Poor (5 sp), \nComfortable (2 gp), and Lavish (10 gp). Lavish inns \nallow players to gain one Temporary Boon the fol-\nlowing day (see Lodging Boons table on pg. 22 of \nthe GM’s Guide).",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Downtime\nThe time you aren’t out adventuring is called \nDowntime. You can spend Downtime to recuper-\nate from your adventures and partake in Downtime \nActivities. Not every moment of Downtime needs to \nbe narrated or roleplayed. Much Downtime can be \nskipped over to get back to adventuring if desired. \nExample Downtime Activities:",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Retrain. Spend time doing activities to retrain",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "any of your chosen abilities or features.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Gather Information. Meet NPCs, pick up news,",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Personal Goals. Pursue goals from your back-",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "story or other smaller quests you’ve chosen.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Buy & Sell. Get new equipment, and sell trea-",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "sures you’ve collected while out adventuring.",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Perform. Play music, tell stories, compete, or",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Craft. Create weapons, armor, or simple items",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Socialize. Build alliances, make new friends, or",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Invest. Use your gold to invest in businesses or",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Mentor. Teach a skill or ability to another char-",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Research. Investigate a mystery, study ancient",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Serve. Aid a patron or a deity in exchange for a",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Build. Establish a home base, start a business,",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "craft siege weapons, or build anything else you can \nimagine (GM and setting-permitting, of course).",
    "page": 18,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Making A Hero\nYour hero is how you will make your mark on the world. Here’s how \nyou can make your own hero:",
    "page": 20,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Step 1: Choose Your Class. This will have the largest impact on the \nother  character choices you make and how you interact with the world \n(see the Heroes book for more details):",
    "page": 20,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•BERSERKER. An unstoppable force of wrath and ruin.\n\t•THE CHEAT. Sneaky, backstabbing, dirty-fighting rogue.\n\t•COMMANDER. A battlefield tactician, leader, and weapon master. \n\t•HUNTER. Resourceful survivalist, bow master, and skilled tracker.\n\t•MAGE. Wield and shape the elements of fire, ice, and lightning.\n\t•OATHSWORN. Faithful guardian, protector, and avenger of the weak. \n\t•SHADOWMANCER. Summon hordes of expendable minions.\n\t•SHEPHERD. Master life and death. Lead a faithful companion.\n\t•SONGWEAVER. Inspiring presence, sharp wit, sharper tongue.\n\t•STORMSHIFTER. Master of weather, beast, and nature.\n\t•ZEPHYR. A disciplined martial artist with swift hands and swift feet.",
    "page": 20,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Step 2: Choose Your Ancestry & Background (and optionally, \nchoose your adventuring motivation). What made your hero want to \nstart adventuring? How do you know the other heroes?",
    "page": 20,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Step 3: Fill in Your Character Sheet. This handy sheet of paper \nhelps you track your stats, abilities, loot, and other important game \ninfo (see pg. 20).",
    "page": 20,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "The Character Sheet\n1. Basic Details & Stats\nFill in your character details: Name, Ancestry, Class, \nLevel, Height, and Weight. Fill in the arrow for your \nadvantaged (+) and disadvantaged (–) Saves, and \nchoose a stat array (recommended: place the high-\nest numbers in the KEY stats for your class).",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Standard: +2, +2, +0, –1 \n\t•Balanced: +2, +1, +1, +0\n\t•Min–Max: +3, +1, –1, –1",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Example. The Cheat has DEX and INT as their KEY stats. \nWith the Min-Max array, you might put +3 in DEX, +1 \nin INT, and –1 in WIL and STR. You’d also mark ▲ for \nDEX saves and ▼ for WIL saves.",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "2. Skill Points\nAt level 1, mark your stat bonuses into each of your \nrespective skills (e.g., a hero with +2 DEX would \nmark +2 in Finesse and Stealth), and then may \nplace 4 additional skill points wherever you like.",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Example. If you have –1 INT; mark –1 for Arcana, Exam-\nination, and Lore. Repeat for your other stats. Then, with \nyour 4 extra points, you could increase Stealth and \nFinesse by +2 each; any 4 skills by 1 each; or dump \nall 4 points into your favorite single skill. Up to you!",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "3. Secondary Stats\nMark your max HP and Hit Dice size (see your class), \nHit Die amount (default: equal to your level), Initia-\ntive (default: DEX), Speed (default: 6), max Wounds \n(default: 6), and inventory slots (10+STR).",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "4. Equipment & Money\nHeroes start at level 1 with the equipment listed for \ntheir class and background OR 50 gp to buy their \nstarting equipment. If starting at a higher level, \nmultiply that by the level you are starting at.",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "But my character is a wealthy noble! That’s fine, \nbut your character only has access to this amount of \ngold for now. Why your wealth is currently inaccessible \nis up to you and your GM; unlocking your full riches \ncould be a great quest!",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "5. Languages\nAll heroes speak Common by default. Each point \nof INT grants you an additional language known. \nThese languages are typically spoken by:",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Common. Most intelligent creatures.\n\t•Dwarvish. Dwarves, Gnomes, and Giants.\n\t•Elvish. Elves, Fey, and Sylvan.\n\t•Goblin. Goblins and Orcs.\n\t•Infernal. Various Fiends and cultists.\n\t•Thieves’ Cant. Scoundrels and rogues.\n\t•Celestial. Celestials and priests.\n\t•Draconic. Dragons, Dragonborn, and Kobolds.\n\t•Primordial. Elementals and Ancient Beings.\n\t•Deep Speak. Underworld dwellers.",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "GROFWINT DRAZLON! Speaking another creature’s \nlanguage can open doors that weapons alone cannot—\nbeing heavily armed without the ability to communi-\ncate often leads to hostility.",
    "page": 21,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "6. Other Abilities\nMark any other special abilities you get from your \nclass, ancestry, background, etc.",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "7. Inventory Slots\nEach hero has 10+STR inventory slots for carry-\ning equipment and loot (held, worn, or in a pack).",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•1 slot can hold a one-handed weapon, shield,",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "worn armor, stack of javelins, 500 gp, or 2 potions.\n\t•2 slots can hold a 2-handed weapon, unworn",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "armor, or similarly bulky items.\n\t•Small, related items can be grouped into one",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "slot for simplicity (e.g., Camping Supplies: soap, \nblanket, brush, rations).",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "On Ammunition. In most games, there’s no need \nto track ammo. If you have a quiver, you have enough \narrows. Assume the hero collects fired arrows, crafts \nmore, or buys them in town.",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Alternatively, your GM may allow you to carry \nwhat you want without the bookkeeping, so long \nas you’re reasonable!",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Leveling Up\nThe GM may allow you to gain a level (LVL) when-\never you complete an appropriately challenging \nquest or adventure. At level 1, this may be as \nsimple as clearing some angry rats out of a base-\nment or rescuing someone from the woods. Each \nsubsequent level will generally take more effort \n(and therefore more time). When a hero gains a \nlevel:",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•HP Increase. Roll your Hit Die with advantage",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "and increase your max HP by that much.\n\t•More Endurance. Your Hit Die max increases",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "by 1 (it is typically equal to your level).\n\t•More Skilled. Gain 1 skill point. Additionally,",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "you may move 1 point from one skill to another \n(as long as the skill doesn’t become negative), \nreflecting your hero’s evolving expertise and \npriorities.",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Note. The maximum bonus a skill can have is +12.",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Class Features. Gain new class features for",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "your level. This may mean increasing your mana \npool, new spells, or even selecting a subclass!\n\t•Other Adjustments. If any of your base stats",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "increase, remember to adjust other elements of \nyour character sheet as needed (skills, damage, \nInitiative, armor, mana, languages, etc.).",
    "page": 22,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Common Ancestries\nYour kin, lineage, heritage, or race—this is how your character was born and how others \nsee you at first glance. You may be a dwarf raised in the mines under the mountain with \ncountless other dwarves, or you may be an elf raised by goblins! It’s up to you to choose \nhow your character began. Choose 1 ancestry and add its bonus to your character sheet.",
    "page": 24,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Human (Medium)\nFound in every terrain and environment, their curiosity and ambition drive them to explore \nevery corner of the world, making them a ubiquitous and versatile race.\nTenacious. +1 to all skills and Initiative.",
    "page": 24,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Dwarf (Medium)\nDwarf, in the old language, means “stone.” You are resilient, solid, stout. Even when driven \nto exhaustion, you will not falter. Forgoing speed, you are gifted with physical vitality and \na belly that can handle the finest (and worst) consumables this world has to offer.\nStout. +2 max Hit Dice, +1 max Wounds, –1 Speed. You know Dwarvish if your INT is \nnot negative.",
    "page": 24,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Elf (Medium)\nElves epitomize swiftness and grace. Their tall, slender forms belie their innate speed, \ngrace, and wit. Formidable in both diplomacy and combat, elves strike swiftly, often pre-\nventing the worst by acting first.\nLithe. Advantage on Initiative, +1 Speed. You know Elvish if your INT is not negative.",
    "page": 24,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "What About Half–Elves? Mix the ancestries however makes sense in your world. You can pick one \nancestral bonus and use it instead of both, or use both half as effectively or half as often.",
    "page": 24,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Halfling (Small)\nKind of like a human, but smaller (except for the feet). Where does our luck come from? \nWell…you know what they say about rabbit feet? Well, we’ve got feet for days compared \nto them. Imagine the amount of luck you could fit into these bad boys!\nElusive.  +1 to Stealth. If you fail a save, you can succeed instead, 1/Safe Rest.",
    "page": 24,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Gnome (Small)\nEccentric, curious, and perpetually optimistic, gnomes are cheerful—especially when com-\npared to their typically grumpier and larger kin, the dwarves. Known for their tinkering, spread-\ning cheer, and playful antics, gnomes pursue their passions with a scatterbrained enthusiasm.\nOptimistic. Allow an ally within Reach 6 to reroll any single die, resets when healed to your \nmax HP. –1 Speed. You know Dwarvish if your INT is not negative (but you call it Gnomish, \nof course).",
    "page": 24,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Flavor Is Free. Want to play a Stout Halfling instead of an Elusive one? An Optimistic Human instead \nof Tenacious? As long as it makes sense and the GM is on board, go for it!",
    "page": 24,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Your setting may or may not support these choices—check with your GM first before selecting one.",
    "page": 25,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Bunbun (Small)\nBunbun are agile and unpredictable, using their \npowerful legs to leap great distances and catch \nfoes off guard. Facing a Bunbun means contend-\ning with an opponent who can strike from unex-\npected angles and swiftly reposition themselves in \nthe heat of battle.\nBunny Legs. Before Interposing or after Defend-\ning (after damage), hop up to your Speed in any \ndirection for free, 1/encounter.",
    "page": 25,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Dragonborn (Medium)\nThe soul of a dragon burns within you, the scales of \nyour body are like forged steel. You are a kiln and your \nheritage the coals that stoke your flames. Call upon \nyour wrath, to speak in the tongue of your ancestors \nand imbue unbridled fury into your attacks.\nDraconic Heritage. +1 Armor. When you attack: \ndeal an additional LVL+KEY damage (ignoring \narmor) divided as you choose among any of your \ntargets; recharges whenever you Safe Rest or gain a \nWound. You know Draconic if your INT is not negative.",
    "page": 25,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Fiendkin (Medium)\nSaid to have been born from the union of man \nand fiend, or from a cursed bloodline, Fiendkin \noften find themselves outcasts in society. Yet, they \nembody determination in the face of adversity. \nTheir ancestors didn’t emerge from the depths of \nthe Everflame to succumb to minor setbacks!\nFlameborn. 1 of your neutral saves is advantaged \ninstead. You know Infernal if your INT is not nega-\ntive.",
    "page": 25,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Goblin (Small)\nGreen, cunning, and perpetually vilified, Goblins \nthrive on the edge of chaos. For a Goblin, vanishing \ninto the shadows is not just a skill—it’s an identity. \nAfter all, what kind of Goblin would you be if you \ncouldn’t slip away unnoticed?\nSkedaddle. Can move 2 spaces for free after you \nbecome the target of an attack or negative effect \n(after damage, ignoring difficult terrain). You know \nGoblin if your INT is not negative.",
    "page": 25,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Kobold (Small)\nSmall, often maniacal, and dragon–obsessed. \nKobolds thrive in the shadows, finding ingenious \nways to survive despite their diminutive size. Under-\nestimated by many, Kobolds prove time and again \nthat even the smallest among us can wield great \npower. \nWily. Force an enemy to reroll a non-critical attack \nagainst you, 1/encounter. +3 to Influence friendly \ncharacters. Advantage on skill checks related to drag-\nons. You know Draconic if your INT is not negative.",
    "page": 25,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Orc (Medium)\nJust when you think you’ve bested a mighty Orc, \nyou’ve merely succeeded in rousing their anger. \nEngaging in combat with an Orc is no endeavor for \nthe weak-willed. While others may cower before \ndeath’s approach, Orcs boldly defy its grasp. \nRelentless. When you would drop to 0 HP, you \nmay set your HP to LVL instead, 1/Safe Rest. +1 \nMight. You know Goblin if your INT is not negative \n(but you call it Orcish, of course).",
    "page": 25,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Flavor Is Free. Want to be a leaping Frogfolk instead of a Bunbun? A Flameborn Kobold? A winged Fairy instead of a \nBirdfolk? A Badgerfolk instead of a Stoatling? As long as it makes sense and your GM is game, go for it!",
    "page": 25,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Birdfolk (Small or Medium)\nBirdfolk find sanctuary not in stone or chains, but \nwithin the boundless expanse of the sky. However, \nthe gift of flight comes at a cost—hollow bones, and \ncommensurate frailty.\nHollow Bones. You have a fly Speed as long as you \nare wearing armor no heavier than Leather. Crits \nagainst you are Vicious (the attacker rolls 1 addi-\ntional die). Forced movement moves you twice as \nfar.",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Celestial (Medium)\nDescendants of divine beings, Celestials carry an aura \nof nobility and grace. Their innate connection to the \nhigher planes allows them to resist the effects of mis-\nfortune, standing strong where others may falter.\nHighborn. Your disadvantaged save is Neutral \ninstead. You know Celestial if your INT isn’t negative.",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Changeling (Medium)\nOften hunted for their silver blood, Changelings \nare natural survivors, slipping into new identities \nwith ease. Changelings that shift too often typi-\ncally aren’t long for the world—they can struggle \nto remember who they once were, becoming little \nmore than reflections of the faces they wear.\nNew Place, New Face. +2 shifting skill points. \nYou may take on the appearance of any ancestry.\nWhen you do, you may place your 2 shifting skill \npoints into any 1 skill. 1/day.",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Crystalborn (Medium)\nFormed from living crystal, the Crystalborn are \nbeings of dazzling beauty and otherworldly tough-\nness. Their translucent bodies refract light and \nsound, granting them unique abilities in combat.\nReflective Aura. When you Defend, gain KEY \narmor and deal KEY damage back to the attacker. \n1/encounter.",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Dryad/Shroomling (Small or Med)\nTied to the natural world, Dryads and Shroomlings \nembody the balance between flora and fauna. Their \nunique physiology releases toxic spores when \nharmed, providing a natural defense against those",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "who dare to harm them.\nDanger Pollen/Spores. Whenever an enemy \ncauses you one or more Wounds, you excrete sop-\norific spores: all adjacent enemies are Dazed. You \nknow Elvish if your INT is not negative.",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Half-Giant (Large)\nTowering beings whose strength is as immovable as \nthe mountains they call home. Their sheer size and \nresilience make them fearsome opponents, capable \nof surviving even devastating blows.\nStrength of Stone. Force an enemy to reroll a \ncrit against you, 1/encounter. +2 Might. You know \nDwarvish if your INT is not negative.",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Minotaur/Beastfolk (Medium)\nMinotaur and other Beastfolk embody a primal \nconnection to The Wild, combining strength with \nnatural agility. Their powerful build allows them to \nmove swiftly, whether repositioning to outflank foes \nor charging in with unstoppable force.\nCharge. When you move at least 4 spaces, you \ncan push a creature in your path. Medium: 1 space; \nSmall/Tiny: up to 2 spaces. 1/turn.",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Oozeling/Construct  (Small or Med)\nWhat even is a “PeOpLe“ anyway? So what if your \nheart pumps oil instead of blood, so what if you \ndon’t even have a heart!? If you can squish yourself \ninto a pair of pants, or swing a sword like everyone \nelse, who’s to say you can’t be a pEOpLe, too?!\nOdd Constitution. Increment your Hit Dice one \nstep (d6 » d8 » d10 » d12 » d20); they always heal \nyou for the maximum amount. Magical healing \nalways heals you for the minimum amount.",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Planarbeing (Medium)\nYou are not from this plane of existence—your soul \nis not as strongly tethered to it as others. But with \nthis vulnerability comes power, the ability to tem-\nporarily shift from one plane to another in times \nof dire need.\nPlaneshift. Whenever you Defend, you can gain \n1 Wound to temporarily phase out of the material \nplane and ignore the damage. –2 max Wounds.",
    "page": 27,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Ratfolk (Small)\nRatfolk are survivors, thriv-\ning in the shadows of society \nwhere others fear to tread. \nAgile, resourceful, and fiercely \nloyal to their own, they have a \nknack for turning scraps into \nsolutions.\nScurry. Gain +2 armor if you \nmoved on your last turn.",
    "page": 28,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Stoatling (Small)\nStoatlings may be small, but they’re \nfar from weak. With fierce determi-\nnation and warrior hearts, they can \ntake down foes many times their \nsize. Their agility and tenacity let \nthem exploit larger enemies’ weak-\nnesses, turning their size into a lethal \nadvantage.\nSmall But Ferocious. Whenever you \nmake a single-target attack against a \ncreature larger than you, roll 1 addi-\ntional d6 for each size category it is \nlarger. They do the same.",
    "page": 28,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Turtlefolk (Small or Med)\nTurtlefolk take their time in everything \nthey do; they are patient, sturdy, and slow \nto anger. They rely on their thick shells for \nprotection, making them difficult to harm, \nbut their cautious movements come at the \ncost of speed.\nSlow & Steady. +4 Armor, –2 speed.",
    "page": 28,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wyrdling (Small)\nUnpredictable and chaotic, Wyrdlings are the \nresult of magic gone awry. Their bodies pulse \nwith raw arcane energy, and their mere pres-\nence often disturbs the balance of magic around \nthem.\nChaotic Surge. Whenever you or a willing ally \nwithin Reach 6 casts a tiered spell, you may allow \nthem to roll on the  Chaos Table. 1/encounter.",
    "page": 28,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Back Out of Retirement. You’ve forgotten more \nthan most adventurers these days know! Talk with \nyour GM, what made you come out of retirement?",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• Let’s see if I remember how to do this...",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "You may gain 1 Wound to use an ability or cast a \nspell as if you were 1 level higher. \n\t• These old bones. Your age has long since",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Devoted Protector. Choose 1 ally in your party. \nYou can survive +3 max Wounds as long as they are \nnearby. Whenever they take a Wound, you do too.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Academy Dropout. School just isn’t for every-\none! You learn by experience in the real world (or \nat least that’s what you tell yourself). Learn any 1 \nUtility Spell.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Made a BAD Choice. Start with 500 or 1000 extra \ngold, or an uncommon/rare magical item (that \nyour GM allows). Gain an equally powerful curse \nor enemy who wants it back. If you choose this back-\nground, your GM may allow you to choose another.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Haunted Past. You are haunted by voices that \noccasionally give you cryptic advice. The voices are \nsometimes VERY helpful. Other times they only \nwant to see you suffer. Advantage against fear.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Ear to the Ground. Advantage on checks to know \nor obtain gossip for events that will soon happen or \nhave happened less than 1 year ago.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "What? I’ve Been Around. 1/per location (or at \nthe GM’s discretion). You happen to know JUST the \nperson who has the information you’re looking for, \nor could get you out of a jam, and… Roll 1d20:",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•1–5. They want you DEAD. \n\t• 6–12. You owe them money.\n\t•13–19. They can be convinced to help you..\n\t• 20. They are your biggest fan/are madly in",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Acrobat. Can be thrown by a larger ally, REALLY far. \nHalf damage from falling and forced movement.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wild One. Whether it is the sticks or flowers in your \nhair, your smell, or the way you carry yourself, wild \ncreatures are less frightened of you and more will-\ning to aid you. +1 Naturecraft. While Field Resting, \nroll your Hit Dice with advantage while in the wild.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Fey Touched. You take half damage from all mag-\nical effects, double from weapons made of metal \n(before armor is applied).",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Survivalist. You never run out of your own per-\nsonal rations. Anything can be food if you try hard \nenough! Advantage against poison saves. +1 max \nHit Die.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Home at Sea. Recover twice as many Wounds and \nHP while resting on a ship or near water. You can fill \nin for a first mate or captain in a pinch. Advantage \non water-related skill checks.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "At Home Underground. You can dig twice as \nfast as others. Safe resting locations underground \nalways count as Lavish lodging for you. You struggle \nto rest (INT save) while it’s raining. “Water… from \nthe SKY?!“",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Raised by Goblins. You speak Goblin natively \n(much better than one who has learned it later in \nlife). You automatically notice and can avoid crude-\nly-made traps and have advantage to notice and \ndisarm more sophisticated traps.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Change It Up! You can choose any other ancestry to \nbe raised by instead, and exchange the known lan-\nguage and get 1 helpful/iconic ability those people \nwould inculcate (e.g., Dwarves know Dwarvish and \nare very good with smithing or stonecraft).",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "History Buff. Advantage on all Lore checks related \nto knowledge about items, facts, or events that hap-\npened more than 100 years ago.",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Backgrounds\nBackgrounds provide a glimpse into your character’s past—how they were raised, the skills they honed \nbefore becoming an adventurer, or even their defining personality traits. Feel free to adapt or reimagine \nthese backgrounds to suit your character’s story. Choose 1 background:",
    "page": 29,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "(Former) Con Artist. You can forge most docu-\nments or mimic voices flawlessly. You have a crim-\ninal contact in most major cities. However, your \nreputation often precedes you—until you prove \nyourself to be trustworthy.",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "(Secretly) Undead. Unnatural Resilience: You \nare immune to disease and do not need to eat, \ndrink, or breathe. Children, animals, and Celes-\ntials are uneasy in your presence; many will be \nhorrified to discover your true nature.",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Taste for the Finer Things. You always have \nup-to-date knowledge of the customs and dress \nof the upper classes and may even know many of \ntheir secrets. Advantage on Influence checks with \nthe upper class.",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Fearless. You are immune to the Frightened con-\ndition. +1 Initiative. –1 Armor.",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "So Dumb I’m Smart Sometimes. (Req. 0 \nor negative INT at character creation.) Reroll an \nINT-related skill check, 1/day. Reroll a failed INT \nsave with advantage, 1/Safe Rest.",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wily Underdog. (Req. 0 or negative STR at char-\nacter creation.) Reroll a failed STR-related roll \n(e.g., STR attack, STR save, Might check) and \nuse another stat instead, 1/day.",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Bumblewise. (Req. 0 or negative WIL at \ncharacter creation.) A result of 1 or less on \nany WIL-related roll counts as a natural 20 \n(WIL save, Naturecraft, Perception, Influence, \nor Insight check).",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Accidental Acrobat. (Req. 0 or negative DEX at \ncharacter creation.) Whenever you fail a DEX-re-\nlated roll (e.g., DEX attack, DEX save, Stealth \ncheck, Finesse check), you may roll again. If \nyou still fail, the consequences are BAD.",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Tradesman/Artisan. Choose a profession \n(Baker/Cook, Smith, Stonemason, Weaver, \nLeatherworker, etc.). Checks you make \nrelated to that profession are made \nwith advantage. You also retain \nspecial knowledge related to your \nprofession.",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Make It Your Own! Remember, backgrounds are \njust a starting point—you’re free to adjust, reimag-\nine, or completely rewrite them to suit your char-\nacter’s story. If you want to know a Utility Spell but \ndon’t like the Academy Dropout flavor, come up \nwith a different reason why your character might \nknow it. Maybe they learned it from a traveling \nbard or discovered it etched into an ancient relic. \n \nFeel free to swap traits, change the flavor text, or blend \nbackgrounds together. Haunted Past might become \nBlessed by Spirits if your character views their other-\nworldly voices as guardians rather than tormentors. \n \nWork with your GM to ensure any changes \nalign with your game’s setting and are bal-\nanced with other backgrounds. These are here \nto inspire creativity—what you build with them is \nentirely up to you!",
    "page": 30,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Adventuring Motivation\nThe world is a dangerous place—people don’t usually just “go adventuring“ without a reason. \nYour motivation should make your character want to work with the rest of the group.",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I owe a life debt to someone in my \nparty. Chat with your party: Who else needs \nhelp with their backstory? What did they do \nto help you?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I owe a LOT of money to some very dan-\ngerous people. What did you do with the \nmoney? Your GM probably has some GREAT \nideas of bad guys you’re in deep with.",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I need to grow in power to defeat some-\none who has wronged me. Do you know \nwho wronged you, or are they unknown? Is \nit an individual or a larger group? Chat with \nyour GM; they’ll love to help fill in the blanks.",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I am searching for a way to bring a loved \none (or someone I hate) back from the \ndead. Who even told you this was possible? \nWhat if they don’t remember you?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I am trying to get back home. Where is \nhome for you, do you even remember? What \ncaused you to leave? Chat with your GM; they \ncan give you some options of homelands.",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I am searching for the one who stole \nsomething valuable from me. Is it an \nobject? A person? A memory? Was it really \nstolen or did you make a bad bargain?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I was polymorphed into another kind \nof creature by a wizard. Hah! How would \nit feel for a cute halfling to become an ugly \ngoblin? What did you do to anger the wizard?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Duty calls. I am honor-bound to serve. \nWho calls you? Your king? Your family? An \nancient alliance or grudge? Talk with your \nGM and other players for ideas and mutual \nconnections.",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I was best friends with (and betrayed \nby) ______. Do you want to win them back? \nGet even? Warn others of their backstabbing? \nTalk with your GM about who this might be.",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I’m lost. Physically? Emotionally? Spiritually? \nAre you in the wrong country or even plane of \nexistence?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wanderlust/Pilgrimage. What amazing \nthing do you want to see or experience? Have \nyou spent too much time away from the road? \nYour GM probably has some fantastic locations \nin mind for you.",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "My home town is in danger. Are you \nlooking for a cure? Mercenaries? Personal \nstrength?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Curiosity! I want to learn the DEEP \nsecrets. Which secrets? Magical, lore, poli-\ntics, what really happened in history?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "To prove my worth. You were always under-\nestimated—by your family, your village, your \npeers, or yourself. What will it take to show \nthem you’re more than they thought? What \nkind of recognition do you seek?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "I’m following a prophecy. A mysterious \nfigure or ancient text foretold that you would \nplay a crucial role in the fate of the world. What \ndo you know of the prophecy? Do you believe it?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Or Make Your Own! A great character back-\nground has connections with the world, its \npeople, your fellow heroes, or even the bad \nguys.  Work with your GM and fellow players \nto find a motivation that will cross paths with \nwhere the story goes. Every good hero has a \ndesire. What’s yours?",
    "page": 32,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Equipment\nEquipment Proficiency. Heroes can use any equipment they like; however, each class has a list of weap-\nons and armor types they are most skilled with. Weapons used without proficiency cannot crit. Defending \nwhile wearing armor worn without proficiency costs 1 additional action.",
    "page": 34,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Swapping Equipment. A hero can sheathe weapons or shields they are proficient with and equip a \ndifferent one for free 1/round.",
    "page": 34,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Deflect! An optional rule for addi-\ntional defensive flexibility: instead of \nadding your shield’s armor to your total \narmor as normal, you may reduce the \ndamage of an attack by your shield’s \narmor value for free 1/round.",
    "page": 34,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Armor\nArmor represents your hero’s ability to dodge or block damage when you use the Defend reaction. While \nunarmored or wearing regular clothes, your Armor is equal to your DEX. Some items may grant additional \nArmor while equipped.",
    "page": 34,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Defend Yourself! If you’re standing right next to a baddie with an axe and you’re not doing anything to defend yourself, \nchances are, you’re going to get axed! (See the “Defend” heroic reaction on pg. 14)",
    "page": 34,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Chain Shirt (Req. 2 STR)\n9+DEX (max 2)\n60 gp",
    "page": 34,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Scale Mail (Req. 3 STR)\n12+DEX (max 2)\n700 gp",
    "page": 34,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Dragonscale (Req. 4 STR)\n15+DEX (max 2)\n3,000 gp",
    "page": 34,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• 2-handed. Can be held in a single hand, but must be wielded in 2 hands to attack with it.\n\t• Load. Some weapons require extra actions to load before each shot.\n\t• Reach. How close an enemy must be to be affected by this attack. If unspecified, Reach 1.\n\t• Range. Attacks can be made from afar. If any enemy is adjacent to you, your Ranged attacks are",
    "page": 35,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "made with disadvantage. Add 1 die of disadvantage to gain +2 Range.\n\t• Thrown. Treat a melee weapon as if it had Range. Once thrown, you no longer have it!\n\t• Vicious. Roll 1 additional die whenever you roll crit damage.",
    "page": 35,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Remember! Only the Primary Die (the leftmost one) is used for determining whether an attack \ncrits. Every time you roll crit damage, roll the additional Vicious die as well!",
    "page": 35,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Dual Wielding\nHeroes may wield 2 Light weapons at the same time. While \ndual wielding, you may gain advantage on an attack with \nthose weapons, 1/round.",
    "page": 35,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "You may dual wield 1-handed weapons without the \nLight property if your STR is 3 or greater, or 1 weapon \nwithout the Light property if your STR is 2. If completely \nunarmed, fists/feet can be considered dual wielded.",
    "page": 35,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Dual wielding different weapons? Roll dice for both weap-\nons and choose either result instead (the 1/round limit still \napplies). Attacking with advantage? Add an extra die for one \nof the weapons.",
    "page": 35,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Unarmed Strikes\nTo attack with your bare hands or feet, roll 1d4; on hit: deal \n1+STR damage.",
    "page": 35,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Improvised Weapons\nUsing an improvised weapon (e.g. a chair, a frying pan, a \nbig rock), default to 1d4+STR or 1d6+STR. Your GM may \nallow you to use bigger dice or other properties if it makes \nsense. An improvised weapon may be likely to break if it \nlands a crit, though!",
    "page": 35,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Customizing Weapons\nCan you reflavor a staff as a greatclub? Sure! A sai instead of \na dagger? Of course! Could you pay a blacksmith to make \nyour 1d12 Greatmaul deal 2d6 or 3d4 damage instead? \nSince the dice all add up to 12, it won’t break the game; \nask your GM! Can a blacksmith make your Dagger deal that \nmuch damage? No, sorry!",
    "page": 35,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Sling\n1d4+DEX Bludgeoning\n2-handed, Range 12, Vicious\n4 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Javelins\n1d6+STR Piercing \nRange 8, Stack of 4\n20 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Throwing Hammers\n1d8+STR Bludgeoning\nRange 4, Stack of 3\n25 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Shortbow\n1d6+DEX Piercing\n2-handed, Range 12\n25 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Longbow\n1d8+DEX Piercing\n2-handed, Range 16 (Req. 1 STR)\n30 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Crossbow\n4d4+DEX Piercing\n2-handed, Load: 1 action, Range 8\n60 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Handheld Ballista\n1d20+DEX Piercing\n2-handed, Load: 2 actions, Range 8 (Req. 2 STR)\n120 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Dagger\n1d4+DEX Piercing\nLight, Thrown 4\n3 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Longsword\n1d8+STR Slashing\n2-handed (1-handed: Req. 2 STR) \n60 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Battleaxe\n1d10+STR Slashing\n2-handed\n30 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Pole Hammer\n1d10+STR Bludgeoning\n2-handed, Reach 2\n60 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Glaive\n1d10+STR Slashing\n2-handed, Reach 2\n60 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Spear\n1d10+STR Piercing\n2-handed, Reach 2\n60 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Greatmaul\n1d12+STR Bludgeoning\n2-handed (Req. 2 STR)\n80 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Greataxe\n2d6+STR Slashing\n2-handed (Req. 2 STR)\n100 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Greatsword\n3d4+STR Slashing/Piercing\n2-handed (Req. 2 STR) \n120 gp",
    "page": 36,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Key Equipment\nHealing Potions\nHealing potions are deep, shimmering red elixirs with a refreshing, effervescent taste. These potions \nare crucial for quick recovery, though their availability is limited. Small towns may have only a few, \nwhile cities offer more (but they are not in unlimited supply). The wealthy often use healing potions \nas a display of affluence, incorporating them into elaborate mixed drinks at social events to showcase \ntheir status.",
    "page": 37,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Potions require one action to drink or to administer to an adjacent willing creature.",
    "page": 37,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Heroes cannot typically see in the dark. Fighting in the dark imposes the Blinded condition. Heroes \ncan bring a lantern or torch to light their way in the dark as long as they have a hand free (or some \nother way) to hold it. A torch typically lasts for 1 dungeon (or 1 level of a very large one). A lamp with \noil can typically last for 1 entire outing, until your next Safe Rest. Torches and lanterns cast  light up to \n6 spaces away; beyond this is darkness.",
    "page": 37,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Be Warned. Denizens of the dark may not appreciate the light and may attack the light bearers \nfirst. Certain spells (e.g., Fire, Lightning, and Radiant) may cause flashes of light as well and draw \nunwanted attention!",
    "page": 37,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Equipment Availability\nCosts for mundane items typically range from a few silver pieces to a few gold pieces. If you can find \nan artisan, you can commission them to create something for you—basically anything you can think of \nthat their level of technology could support. The more ornate, the higher the price. Commissioning the \ncreation of a special item will typically start around 50 gp and only go up from there. Smaller towns will \nhave fewer items and artisans than larger cities.",
    "page": 37,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Healing Potion\n(action) Heal 2d4+4 HP.\n50 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Greater Healing Potion\n(action) Heal 3d6+6 HP.\n150 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Supreme Healing Potion\n(action) Heal 4d8+8 HP.\n450 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Torch (stack of 2)\nFor when it’s dark. 1 use each.\n5 sp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Lantern & Oil\nLike a torch, but not as cool (refill: 1 gp). \n10 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Vial of Pitch\nSticky, and VERY flammable.\n2 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Rope (50 ft.)\nYou always need rope.\n10 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Chain (10 ft.)\nLike rope, but stronger (and heavy).\n50 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Bucket\nAlso works as a hat in a pinch!\n1 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Mirror\nFor medusas AND spinach teeth.\n4 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Magnifying Glass\nMake the small, big.\n5 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Shovel\nSometimes you need a hole dug.\n3 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Grappling Hook\nFor climbing or catching BIG fish.\n4 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Quiver & Ammo\nDon’t leave home without it.\n10 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Shiny Object\nWorthless, but VERY pretty.\n1 sp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Hunting Trap\nSnap snap, don’t lose a finger!\n10 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Camping Supplies\nBedroll, rations, simple tent.\n5 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Pitons\nMetal spikes, for sealing doors.\n5 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Manacles\nFor when someone has been bad.\n3 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Instrument\nDrums, Horn, Lyre, Flute, etc. \n5–50 gp",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "What About…? These are \nnot all of the items available \nfor purchase, merely a sam-\npling. If you can think of it, \nyou can likely buy it!",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Currency is made up of \nSilver (sp) and Gold pieces \n(gp). 10 silver = 1 gold. 1 sp \nis roughly the cost of a humble \nmeal; 1 gp, a sumptuous feast. \nMost small towns will have \nequipment and items worth \n50 gp or less. You’ll need to \nadventure to larger towns \nor cities or find a traveling \nmerchant to purchase more \nvaluable pieces of equipment.",
    "page": 38,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Uncommon\nTypically found around levels 2-6\n50–500+ gp",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Rare\nTypically found around levels 5-12\n500–5,000+ gp",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Very Rare\nTypically found around levels 8-18\n5,000–500,000+ gp",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Legendary\nTypically found around levels 15-20\n1,000,000+gp or Priceless",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Weapon of Many Hands (Rarity varies)\nWhile equipped, this weapon grants the wearer \nadditional arms. The wearer can use the extra arms \nto perform any task their normal hands can do \n(wield equipment, Grapple enemies, climb, etc.) \nbut does not allow the wearer to perform actions any \nfaster. These extra appendages may be horrifying \nto people in polite society. A weapon that grants 1 \nextra hand is likely to be uncommon; 4 extra hands, \nlegendary.",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Extra Arms?! Yes, you can dual wield 2-handed weap-\nons or wear more than 1 shield, or Grapple 2 different \ncreatures while hitting them both at the same time! \nOr any number of creative things, provided you have \nthe arms to perform the task.",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Harbinger & Sovereign, \nAbyssal’s Claim (Legendary Glaives)\nSet of 2 matching glaives, +4 extra arms while both \nare equipped.",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Weapon of Animosity\nWhenever you attack with this weapon, roll an addi-\ntional animosity die. The weapon deals that much \nadditional damage to your target on a hit. When-\never this weapon misses, you take that damage \ninstead. A weapon that adds 1d4 is likely to be \nuncommon; 1d10 or greater, legendary.",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Weapon of Slaying\nWhenever you attack with this weapon, it deals an \nadditional die of damage against a particular crea-\nture type. Those creatures may try to kill you first. A \n1d4 weapon of slaying is likely to be uncommon; \n+1d10 or more, legendary.",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Gnatbane Weapon (Uncommon)\nDoes not miss Small or Tiny creatures (they may \nhate you for it and attack you first).",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Though some magical items can be purchased, most cannot. Some special shops may have a very small \nselection of them to purchase, but more typically these powerful items are acquired through adventuring.",
    "page": 40,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "When you land a hit with this weapon, you may \nsuffer 1d6 damage to deal twice that much addi-\ntional damage to your target.",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "While equipped, you have –1 to saves you roll and \n+1 to your save DC.",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Mindlink Daggers (Rare)\nA matched pair of slender, silver daggers with inter-\ntwining runes. Enables the sharing of thoughts \nbetween any who holds (or is stabbed by) one.",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Bloodstained Quill (Uncommon)\nIf you dip this quill into the blood of a dead intelli-\ngent creature, the quill animates and writes the last \nwords spoken by that creature.",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Eyes of the Street (Uncommon)\nA pair of goggles covered in muck that you can’t ever \nclean off completely. While wearing them, you can \nlook at a rat or a pigeon to gain the ability to see and \nhear through its senses for 10 minutes. Once you use \nthis ability, you must whisper a secret to the goggles \nbefore you can use them again. That secret always \nseems to become a local rumor before too long….",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Handwraps of Force (Rare)\nWhile wearing these wraps, whenever you make \nan unarmed strike, you may push your target up \nto 2 spaces and yourself the same distance in the \nopposite direction. You may instead make an attack \nwith no target, striking the air to propel yourself 4 \nspaces in any direction.",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Resolute Fangs, Golden Bastion\n(Legendary Shield)\n+8 Armor. Reaction: When you reduce damage",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "from a melee attack with this shield, it may Grapple \nthe attacker regardless of its size (escape DC 20 STR, \nmax 1 creature). Action: Speak this shield’s com-\nmand word to make it immovable, fixed in place, \nuntil it is spoken again.",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Key of Doors (Very Rare)\nInsert this key into any locked door to open it, not to \nthe room beyond, but to any doorway you’ve previ-\nously walked through while holding this item.",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Grim Coronet (Rare)\nWhen you would die while wearing this crown, gain \n3 actions and take a turn immediately. You die at \nthe end of your turn.",
    "page": 41,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "KEY OF DOORS\nRESOLUTE FANGS,  \nGOLDEN BASTION",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Vindication (Legendary Weapon of Animosity)",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "A jagged blade marred by scorch marks and dark \nstains, radiating a bitter, vengeful energy that pun-\nishes both wielder and foe alike. +1d12 damage. \nYou take this damage on a miss.",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Pocket Cauldron (Rare)\nWhile Safe Resting, use this to brew your choice of \n1 potion, to be consumed immediately:",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "• Elixir of Futuresight: This potion grants the",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "drinker a brief, cryptic vision of a future event.\n\t• Elixir of Requiem: This potion allows the",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "drinker to relive a crucial memory from their past.\n\t• Elixir of Time: Once every 100 years, the caul-",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "dron can brew a potion that can take the drinker \nback in time 1 day.",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Phoenix Helm (Legendary)\nIf you die while wearing this golden helm, your body \nexplodes in flames and hot ash. You rise anew from \nthe ashes... (see pg. 19 of the GM’s Guide for more).",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Ball of Spiders (Uncommon)\nA black, palm-sized ball with faintly writhing pat-\nterns etched into its surface. Action: Throw this ball",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "up to 6 spaces. Upon impact, it shatters, releasing a \nswarm of harmless but horrifyingly realistic spectral \nspiders that cover a 2x2 area. Creatures in the area \nmust make a WIL save or be Frightened until the \nend of their next turn. Once used, the ball reforms \nat the next Safe Rest.",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Skitter Shoes (Rare)\nWhile wearing these shoes, you can walk on vertical \nsurfaces or ceilings as if they were flat ground, but \nonly at half your normal Speed. If you end your turn \nupside down or on a vertical surface, you must make \na DC 10 STR save or fall down, landing prone.",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Button of Protection (Rare)\nA small, unassuming button etched with a faintly \nglowing sigil. When sewn onto an outfit, as a \nreaction when you are attacked, you may pull the \nbutton off and throw it into the air. The button emits \na sudden, dazzling flash of light and a high-pitched \nwhistle. The attacker must make a WIL save or be \ndistracted, causing the attack to miss you.",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "After use, the button becomes inert. It can be \nsewn back onto a garment during a Safe Rest by an \nexperienced seamstress or tailor with silver thread, \nwhich reactivates its power.",
    "page": 42,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Spell Scrolls\nSpell scrolls are single-use inscribed magical spells. Casting a spell \nwith a spell scroll does not cost mana, nor does it require magical \nability. Anyone who can read the language the scroll is written in can \nutilize it. Reading one aloud takes the same number of actions the \nspell normally takes and consumes the scroll.",
    "page": 43,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "A character must succeed on a DC 10 Arcana check to cast it suc-\ncessfully if they do not already know a spell from that school; on a \nfailure, it is wasted. Spell tier and typical price:",
    "page": 43,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wands\nLike spell scrolls, these can be used to cast spells without consuming \nmana and do not require magical ability. Unlike spell scrolls, wands \ncan be recharged and used again. Characters proficient with wands \ncan use one from any spell school, spending only the normal amount \nof actions to cast the spell.",
    "page": 43,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Characters not proficient with wands must succeed on a DC \n10+spell tier Arcana check to successfully cast the spell. Success \nor failure, the charge is spent. Typical wand prices and examples:",
    "page": 43,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wand of Firestep\nUncommon wand, Cantrip (3 charges)\nRecharge: Heat the wand in a blacksmith’s forge \nuntil it glows, then quench it in oil.",
    "page": 44,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wand of Dread Visage\nUncommon wand, Tier 2 (2 charges)\nRecharge: Place the wand in a freshly slain corpse. \nLeave it until only bones remain.",
    "page": 44,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wand of Fly\nUncommon wand, Tier 3 (2 charges)\nRecharge: Give it to a wild bird and let it fly freely. \nRetrieve it wherever the bird drops it.",
    "page": 44,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wand of Glacier Strike\nVery Rare wand, Tier 8 (1 charge)\nRecharge: Leave the wand at the bottom of a lake \nuntil it freezes over and thaws naturally.",
    "page": 44,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wand of Ride the Lightning\nVery Rare wand, Tier 6 (2 charges)\nRecharge: Place at the highest point within 1 mile. \nRetrieve after 3 thunderstorms.",
    "page": 44,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wand of Barrier of Wind\nRare wand, Tier 2 (3 charges)\nRecharge: Hang the wand with wind chimes in a \nbreezy area. Let it ring for 3 days.",
    "page": 44,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Wand of Sacrifice\nVery Rare wand, Tier 6 (1 charge)\nRecharge: Plant it in a new garden, leave it undis-\nturbed until the flowers bloom.",
    "page": 44,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Elderwyrm’s Majesty\nLegendary wand, Tier 9 (1 charge) \nThis wand can cast Dragonform, turning into the \ntype of dragon that last charged it.\nRecharge: Give an ancient dragon a gift it truly \ndesires.",
    "page": 44,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Heartwood, Splinter of the Tree \nof Life\nLegendary wand, Tier 9 (1 charge)\nCast Redeem with no required components.\nRecharge: A sacred hymn must be sung over it \nceaselessly for 100 years.",
    "page": 44,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Spells\nThere are 6 main schools of magic. Each school has its own basic spells called cantrips and 9 \ntiers of progressively more powerful spells that can be unlocked as heroes level up. Heroes \ncan cast any spell from the schools that they know within the tiers they have unlocked.",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Mana. Powerful tiered spells require mana—a portion of the spellcaster’s life force—to \nfuel them. A spell’s mana cost is equal to its tier. See the Heroes book for more info on \nhow different classes gain mana. Cantrips, cost no mana.",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Upcasting. You can spend additional mana on tiered spells (up to the tier that you \nhave unlocked) to make them stronger for each additional mana spent.",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Multi-Target/Area of Effect (AoE).  Multi-target/AoE attacks follow special rules to \nstreamline play: they do not miss or crit, and a single roll is applied to all targets. (Ignore \n(dis)advantage from conditions on individual targets—such as Blinded or Grappled—though \nanything granting you (dis)advantage still applies to your roll as normal.)",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Save Spells. A hero’s save DC is typically 10+KEY.",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Range and Reach. Just like weapons, spells with “Range” can target creatures from a distance, but \nare cast with disadvantage if any enemy is adjacent to you. Add 1 die of disadvantage to gain +2 \nRange (max +6). Spells with “Reach” can’t do this, but they are cast as normal even when in melee.",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "•Fire Spells. Deal high, consistent damage at medium range. Some fire spells can inflict the",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "Smoldering condition and gain additional destructive effects against Smoldering enemies.\n\t•Ice Spells. Deal medium damage at long range, with a focus on controlling the bat-",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "tlefield and protecting the spellcaster. Some ice spells have additional effects against \nHampered targets.\n\t•Lightning Spells. Deal high damage at long range with a focus on teleporting around",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "the battlefield and taking advantage of creatures equipped with metal. However, some \nlightning spells may fail to find ground and damage the spellcaster instead.\n\t•Necrotic Spells. Summon horrible minions or manipulate and trap targets. Some risky",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "necrotic spells prey upon damaged creatures, sapping their very life force—but frequently \nfail to distinguish between friend and foe.\n\t•Radiant Spells. Can obliterate the unholy, the fearful, and those who would dare harm",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "you or your allies. Equally effective at a distance or in melee. Other spells can protect, \nmend wounds, and even restore creatures back to life!\n\t•Wind Spells. Aid in moving friend and foe alike around the battlefield. They can also",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
    "text": "slice and cut through entire groups of foes and viciously deal extra damage on critical hits.",
    "page": 46,
    "source": "CoreRules-2.0.1.pdf"
  },
  {
